ls-peasants, day-laborers, city council members, teachers, shopkeepers-were charged with myriad offenses. Seeking to make sense of this violence and its aftermath, The Plunder examines the circulation of antisemitic ideas within Galicia against the political backdrop of the Habsburg state. Daniel Unowsky sees the 1898 anti-Jewish riots as evidence not of Galician backwardness and barbarity, but of a late nineteenth-century Europe reeling from economic, cultural, and political transformations wrought by mass politics, literacy, industrialization, capitalist agriculture, and government expansion. Through its nuanced analysis of the riots as a form of "exclusionary violence," this book offers new insights into the upsurge of the antisemitism that accompanied the emergence of mass politics in Europe at the turn of the twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aAntisemitismzGalicia (Poland and Ukraine)xHistoryy19th century. 0aAntisemitism-Galicia (Poland and Ukraine)-History-19th century. 0aGalicia (Poland and Ukraine)-Ethnic relations-Political aspects-History-19th century. 0aJewsxCrimes againstzGalicia (Poland and Ukraine)xHistoryy19th century. 0aPolitical violencezGalicia (Poland and Ukraine)xHistoryy19th century. 0aRiotszGalicia (Poland and Ukraine)xHistoryy19th century. 0aRiots-Galicia (Poland and Ukraine)-History-19th century. 4aCatholicism. 4aGalicia. 4aHabsburg. 4aJews. 4aPoland. 4aantisemitism. 4apeasant. 4ariot. 4atrials. 4aviolence. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Eastern.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311070368940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781503606104zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503606104423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503606104.j